# `.github/public-mirror/`

Plumbing for the read-only public mirror at
[`TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public`](https://github.com/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public).

## Contents

- `paths.allowlist` ŌĆö paths shipped to the mirror by `git-filter-repo`.
  Anything not on this list is excluded.
- `mailmap` ŌĆö rewrites private commit-author emails to a
  `<localpart>@global-claude-config.local` form for the mirror.
- `replacements.txt` ŌĆö `git-filter-repo` replacement rules used for
  **both** `--replace-text` (blob content) and `--replace-message`
  (commit messages). This is the value-scrubbing pass: it rewrites
  specific values (personal paths, AWS account IDs, SSO profile names,
  cluster/repo/org names, and the `ExampleProject`/`example-` prose
  tokens) out of the content that *does* ship, as defense in depth on
  top of the path allowlist. Ordering matters ŌĆö filter-repo applies
  rules in file order, so compound identifiers (full
  `<RoleName>-<AccountID>` SSO profiles, full cluster names) are listed
  before any prefix or substring that would also match them, and the
  blanket prose sweeps come last. See the comment header in the file.
  **The workflow does not feed this file to filter-repo directly.**
  filter-repo's `--replace-text` / `--replace-message` parsers do not
  skip `#`-prefixed lines (unlike `--paths-from-file`), so a bare `#`
  comment line would parse as the literal rule `# -> ***REMOVED***` and
  corrupt every `#` in every mirrored blob and commit message
  (shebangs, comments, markdown headings ŌĆö issue #157). The workflow
  therefore keeps only real rule lines via an allow-list grep
  (`grep -E '^(literal:|regex:|glob:)'`) into an ephemeral
  `replacements.clean.txt` and points both flags at that cleaned copy.
  Because every rule carries an explicit `literal:`/`regex:`/`glob:`
  prefix, the allow-list both drops comments and blank lines and lets a
  rule's match-text safely begin with `#` (a deny-list `grep -v '^#'`
  would wrongly strip such a rule). The cleaned file is a runtime CI
  artifact: it is written under this directory (which is excluded from
  the allowlist), is `.gitignore`d so it can never be accidentally
  committed, and never reaches the mirror. The workflow's input
  fingerprint hashes this cleaned rule set, so a comment-only edit to
  `replacements.txt` does not trigger a refilter and force-push.
- `CONTRIBUTORS.template` ŌĆö header text prepended to the auto-generated
  `CONTRIBUTORS` file. The workflow rebuilds the file content on every
  run and only commits when the resulting blob differs from the one at
  the current `HEAD:CONTRIBUTORS` (so a run with no new contributors
  produces no new commit).
- `../workflows/public-mirror.yml` ŌĆö the GitHub Actions workflow that
  filters the repo, regenerates `CONTRIBUTORS` (skipped when the blob
  is unchanged), and pushes to the mirror's `main` (skipped when the
  new local tip already equals the mirror's current tip), plus two
  bookkeeping branches on the mirror that persist filter-repo state
  across runs.

### Workflow behavior

- Stable public SHAs across runs. The filter step runs
  `git filter-repo --state-branch filter-repo-state
  --prune-empty=never`, so unchanged source commits keep their
  previously-computed public SHAs across runs. A genuine source
  change appends commits as a fast-forward; a consumer's `git pull`
  fast-forwards cleanly instead of seeing the entire history
  rewritten.
- Two bookkeeping branches live on the mirror (not in this repo):
  - `filter-repo-state` ŌĆö owned by `git filter-repo`; holds the
    persisted fast-import marks (source-commit ŌåÆ public-commit SHA
    mapping).
  - `filter-repo-meta` ŌĆö owned by the workflow; holds a single
    `inputs.sha256` blob with a sha256 fingerprint of
    `paths.allowlist` + `mailmap` + `replacements.txt`. Used to detect
    config changes that invalidate the persisted marks.
  Both are always pushed (with `--force`) at the end of each run so
  the next run can read them back. The state branch is rewritten by
  filter-repo on a refilter; the meta branch is rebuilt fresh each
  run with pinned author/committer dates, so a no-op meta push is a
  true no-op when the fingerprint is unchanged.
- Editing `paths.allowlist`, `mailmap`, or `replacements.txt` triggers
  a detected full refilter on the next run. The workflow logs three
  `::warning::` annotations together: the reason
  (one of "first run (no state branch on mirror)", "meta branch
  missing or unreadable on mirror", or "filter inputs changed
  (paths.allowlist, mailmap, or replacements.txt edited)"), the
  consequence
  ("force-push the mirror's main and rewrite all public SHAs"), and
  the consumer action ("one-time
  `git fetch && git reset --hard origin/main`"). Steady-state runs
  (no source change, no config change) print
  `Filter inputs unchanged; reusing persisted marks from state branch.`
  and produce a no-op push to `main`.
- `--prune-empty=never` is a deliberate trade-off paired with
  `--state-branch` (filter-repo's source warns that empty-commit
  pruning does not work well with `--state-branch`). Source commits
  that touch only excluded paths (`.claude/`, `designs/`, `memory/`,
  etc.) show up in the public history as empty commits with the
  original commit message intact. Leaking both activity timing AND
  the commit-message contents for changes touching only excluded
  paths is the accepted cost for SHA stability; the excluded diff
  payload itself stays excluded.
- The first run after this change lands is a one-time SHA-scheme
  switch: filter-repo has no persisted marks yet, so it rebuilds
  history from scratch and force-pushes a rewritten `main`.
  Consumers reset once; subsequent runs are fast-forward.
- The bare clone is made with `git clone --no-local --bare
  "file://$PWD/.git"` so it is single-packed before filter-repo runs.
  filter-repo's from-scratch path enforces a freshness check
  ("expected freshly packed repo") that requires a single pack
  (packs <= 1) with no non-replace-ref loose objects. A plain
  `git clone --bare .` from the Actions checkout takes git's
  local-clone hardlink path, which mirrors the source's pack layout;
  the Actions checkout is multi-packed, so the clone ends up with two
  packs and trips the check's `packs > 1` clause, aborting the run
  before any history is rewritten (issue #160). `--no-local` via a
  `file://` URL forces the real transfer protocol, which sends a
  single packfile (count 0, packs 1); the `file://` form is required
  because a plain path can still trigger the local-clone optimization
  even with `--no-local` on some git versions. This supersedes the
  earlier `git gc` remediation (issues #160/#162): `git gc` cleared
  loose objects but left the two packs (two is below git's gc
  pack-consolidation threshold), so the freshness check still aborted.
  The workflow does NOT pass `git filter-repo --force` ŌĆö the
  maintainer argues against bypassing the check, and making the clone
  genuinely fresh is the correct fix. The clone keeps a single remote
  named `origin`, so it leaves the one-remote-named-`origin`
  constraint (above) intact.

## Mirror posture (manually applied ŌĆö POC for issue #66)

The mirror is configured as **read-only for code, open for issues**.
External users can file issues against the public repo; we triage and
fix them in the upstream private repo. PRs cannot land.

This posture was reached by hand on 2026-05-17. The configuration is
not declared as IaC in this repo ŌĆö the
[`repo-public-mirror-setup`](../../skills/repo-public-mirror-setup.md)
skill (tracked by [#66](https://github.com/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config/issues/66))
is the canonical declaration. Re-running that skill against the mirror
should be **idempotent**: it should reconcile the live state to what
the skill specifies, with no manual cleanup required.

### Target configuration

On the mirror repo (`TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public`):

- Repo settings:
  - `has_issues=true`
  - `has_projects=false`, `has_wiki=false`, `has_discussions=false`
  - `allow_merge_commit=true` (forced ŌĆö see "Gotchas" below)
  - `allow_squash_merge=false`, `allow_rebase_merge=false`
  - `delete_branch_on_merge=true`
- Branch protection on `main`: **none** (replaced by ruleset; see below).
- Ruleset on `refs/heads/main`:
  - Name: `mirror-main-readonly`
  - Enforcement: `active`
  - Rules: `update`, `deletion`, `non_fast_forward` (blocks normal
    pushes, branch deletion, and force-pushes for non-bypass actors)
  - Bypass actors: repo admin (`actor_id: 5`, `actor_type:
    RepositoryRole`, `bypass_mode: always`)
- Deploy key:
  - Title: `public-mirror-workflow`
  - `read_only: false` (must be writable so the workflow can force-push)
  - Private half stored as the `PUBLIC_MIRROR_DEPLOY_KEY` secret on the
    *upstream* (private) repo

### How it was applied

```bash
# Enable Issues
gh api -X PATCH repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public \
  -f has_issues=true

# Create the ruleset (payload in JSON below)
gh api -X POST repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public/rulesets \
  --input ruleset.json

# Delete the old branch protection (rulesets supersede it)
gh api -X DELETE \
  repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public/branches/main/protection
```

Ruleset JSON:

```json
{
  "name": "mirror-main-readonly",
  "target": "branch",
  "enforcement": "active",
  "bypass_actors": [
    {
      "actor_id": 5,
      "actor_type": "RepositoryRole",
      "bypass_mode": "always"
    }
  ],
  "conditions": {
    "ref_name": {
      "include": ["~DEFAULT_BRANCH"],
      "exclude": []
    }
  },
  "rules": [
    { "type": "deletion" },
    { "type": "non_fast_forward" },
    { "type": "update" }
  ]
}
```

### Verification

After applying:

```bash
gh api repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public --jq \
  '{has_issues, has_projects, has_wiki, allow_merge_commit,
    allow_squash_merge, allow_rebase_merge}'
# expect: {has_issues: true, allow_merge_commit: true, others: false}

gh api repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public/branches/main/protection
# expect: 404 "Branch not protected"

gh api repos/TheVoskamps/global-claude-config-public/rulesets \
  --jq '.[] | {name, enforcement}'
# expect: {name: "mirror-main-readonly", enforcement: "active"}
```

Then manually trigger the mirror workflow to confirm the deploy-key
push still passes through the ruleset:

```bash
gh workflow run public-mirror.yml --ref main
```

### Gotchas (for the skill to handle)

1. **GitHub refuses to disable all three merge methods.** A
   `PATCH` with `allow_merge_commit=false, allow_squash_merge=false,
   allow_rebase_merge=false` returns:

   > "Sorry, you need to allow at least one merge strategy."
   > `(no_merge_method)`

   So we leave `allow_merge_commit=true`. The PR Merge button is *not*
   greyed out ŌĆö but the ruleset on `main` blocks any PR merge from
   landing anyway, so this is harmless. The skill should pick one
   merge method (merge-commit is the least disruptive) and leave the
   others off.

2. **Deploy keys with write access bypass branch rulesets natively.**
   Our `bypass_actors` configuration uses `RepositoryRole id 5`
   (admin). The workflow's force-push succeeded under the new ruleset
   even though the deploy key is not associated with any repository
   role ŌĆö rulesets don't enforce against deploy keys the same way they
   do against users. This means the admin-role bypass is
   **belt-and-suspenders**, not load-bearing: the workflow would still
   work without it. We keep it so that if the workflow auth ever
   migrates to a PAT or app installation owned by an admin user, the
   bypass is already in place.

3. **PRs cannot be disabled at the repo level.** GitHub has no
   `has_pull_requests` toggle. External users can still open PRs
   against the mirror; the merge will fail because the push to `main`
   is blocked by the ruleset. The README banner tells them to file
   issues instead and explains that fixes happen upstream.

4. **Rulesets supersede branch protection.** We delete the
   pre-existing branch protection after creating the ruleset. Leaving
   both in place is allowed by GitHub but causes confusing
   double-evaluation. The skill should delete branch protection if
   present whenever the ruleset is reconciled.

5. **The allowlist must not ship `.github/`.** The mirror workflow's
   force-push uses a deploy key, which lacks the `workflow` OAuth
   scope. Pushing a commit that touches `.github/workflows/` would
   fail with:

   > "refusing to allow an OAuth App to create or update workflow ...
   > without `workflow` scope"

   So `.github/` is excluded from the allowlist by design, which means
   this directory (`.github/public-mirror/`) ŌĆö including this README ŌĆö
   never ships to the mirror. That's correct: it's upstream-only
   plumbing.

### What the skill needs to do (issue #66)

When run against a fresh repo: create everything above from scratch.
When re-run against an existing mirror: reconcile each piece
idempotently ŌĆö skip if matched, update if drifted, delete if extra
(e.g. a recreated branch protection). The skill's first phase
(deploy-key creation, workflow file installation, allowlist+mailmap
templates) is already idempotent in the existing implementation; the
posture configuration above is the gap this issue closes.
